Part 1 - Data File¶

We picked the "Cardiovascular Diseases Risk Prediction Dataset".

In [ ]:
data = pd.read_csv('CVD_cleaned.csv')
len(data)

Short description¶

The data consists of 19 variables, which describe the health and lifestyle of a person. These factors can be contributed to being at risk with any form of Cardiovascular Diseases.

The data was collected in a survey by The Behavioral Risk Factor Surveillance System in the USA. It contains 308854 rows and 19 columns.

Link to the source¶

https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/alphiree/cardiovascular-diseases-risk-prediction-dataset?resource=download

Data transformations¶

Tranformation 1 - Changing the diabities feature to be categorical with 3 options.

First we will change variable name in the diabities feature from 'No, pre-diabetes or borderline diabetes' to 'at risk', in order to define it as a more general category. In addition, we will remove records with the value 'Yes, but female told only during pregnancy' from the feature, because it could be caused by Gestational diabetes - which is a temporary condition that occurs during pregnancy. We don't want to include this in our analysis, because it might not a permanent condition, and we don't want to change it to one of the other values to avoid unintentional changes to the meaning of the data.

In [ ]:
data.loc[data["Diabetes"] == 'No, pre-diabetes or borderline diabetes', "Diabetes"] = 'at risk'
data = data[data["Diabetes"] != 'Yes, but female told only during pregnancy']

Transformation 2 - Adding a numerical age category variable.

We noticed the age category has categories by age, each category has a range of age in a string. We decided to add a numerical age variable, in order to create an order relation between the categories. We describe the age category by the lowest age in the range.

In [ ]:
data["Numerical_Age_Category"] = data["Age_Category"].apply(lambda x: int(x[:2]))

Detailed Description of Columns:¶

General_Health:

  • Type: categorical
  • Unique values: ['Poor', 'Fair', 'Good', 'Very Good', 'Excellent']
  • Missing values: 0
  • Description: General health status as described by the individual.

Checkup:

  • Type: categorical
  • Unique values: ['Never', '5 or more years ago', 'Within the past 5 years', 'Within the past years', 'Within the past year']
  • Missing values: 0
  • Description: Last visit to a doctor for a routine checkup.

Exercise:

  • Type: binary
  • Missing values: 0
  • Description: Whether the individual exercised in the past month other than their regular job.

Heart_Disease:

  • Type: binary
  • Missing values: 0
  • Description: Indicates whether the individual has been diagnosed with heart disease.

Skin_Cancer:

  • Type: binary
  • Missing values: 0
  • Description: Indicates whether the individual has been diagnosed with skin cancer.

Other_Cancer:

  • Type: binary
  • Missing values: 0
  • Description: Indicates whether the individual has been diagnosed with types of cancer other than skin cancer.

Depression:

  • Type: binary
  • Missing values: 0
  • Description: Indicates whether the individual has been diagnosed with depression.

Diabetes:

  • Type: categorical
  • Unique values: ['No', 'at risk', 'Yes']
  • Missing values: 0
  • Description: Indicates whether the individual has been diagnosed with diabetes or is at risk of diabetes.

Arthritis:

  • Type: binary
  • Missing values: 0
  • Description: Indicates whether the individual has been diagnosed with arthritis.

Sex:

  • Type: categorical
  • Unique values: ['Male', 'Female']
  • Missing values: 0
  • Description: Sex of the individual.

Age_Category:

  • Type: categorical
  • Unique values: ['18-24', '25-29', '30-34', '35-39', '40-44', '45-49', '50-54', '55-59', '60-64', '65-69', '70-74', '75-79', '80+']
  • Missing values: 0
  • Description: Age category of the individual.

Height_(cm):

  • Type: numerical (float)
  • Missing values: 0
  • Description: Height of the individual in centimeters.

Weight_(kg):

  • Type: numerical (float)
  • Missing values: 0
  • Description: Weight of the individual in kilograms.

BMI:

  • Type: numerical (float)
  • Missing values: 0
  • Description: Body Mass Index (BMI) of the individual, calculated from height and weight.

Smoking_History:

  • Type: binary
  • Missing values: 0
  • Description: Smoking history of the individual.
Note: We saw in the documentation that the following columns, regarding consumption, are measured in units per month. From our knowledge of the domain, we assume that these variables are numerical and not categorical - for example, it is possible to consume half a glass of alcohol per month.¶

Alcohol_Consumption:

  • Type: numerical (float)
  • Missing values: 0
  • Description: Amount of alcohol consumption by the individual per month.

Fruit_Consumption:

  • Type: numerical (float)
  • Missing values: 0
  • Description: Frequency of fruit consumption by the individual per month.

Green_Vegetables_Consumption:

  • Type: numerical (float)
  • Missing values: 0
  • Description: Frequency of green vegetables consumption by the individual per month.

FriedPotato_Consumption:

  • Type: numerical (float)
  • Missing values: 0
  • Description: Frequency of fried potato consumption by the individual per month.

Numerical_Age_Category:

  • Type: categorical
  • Unique values: ['18', '25', '30', '35', '40', '45', '50', '55', '60', '65', '70', '75', '80']
  • Missing values: 0
  • Description: Numerical indication of age category of the individual.

We noticed that the alohol consumtion graph was unbalances since there were a lot of people who reported 0. Based on the example we saw in the tutorial, we are presenting an additional boxplot to show the outliers where we dont consider the people who reported 0.

In [ ]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

numerical_variables_list = []
categorical_variables_list = []

for variable_name in data.columns:
    if data[variable_name].dtype == "object" or variable_name == "Numerical_Age_Category":
        categorical_variables_list.append(variable_name)
    else:
        numerical_variables_list.append(variable_name)

# for every numerical variable make histogram and report of mean, variance, median, min, max
for variable_name in numerical_variables_list:
    if variable_name != "Alcohol_Consumption":
        print(variable_name)
        print(f"mean: {data[variable_name].mean():.3f}")
        print(f"variance: {data[variable_name].var():.3f}")
        print("median: ", data[variable_name].median())
        print("min: ", data[variable_name].min())
        print("max: ", data[variable_name].max())

        # Report on outliers - values that are outside the whiskers of the boxplot
        q1 = data[variable_name].quantile(0.25)
        q3 = data[variable_name].quantile(0.75)
        iqr = q3 - q1
        lower_bound = q1 - (1.5 * iqr)
        upper_bound = q3 + (1.5 * iqr)
        print("total number of outliers: ", len(data[(data[variable_name] < lower_bound) | (data[variable_name] > upper_bound)]))
        print("number of outliers above: ", len(data[data[variable_name] > upper_bound]))
        print("number of outliers below: ", len(data[data[variable_name] < lower_bound]))
        

        # Create a figure with two subplots side by side
        fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=2, figsize=(12, 6))

        # Plot histogram in the first subplot
        axes[0].hist(data[variable_name], bins=30)

        if variable_name in ["Fruit_Consumption", "Green_Vegetables_Consumption", "FriedPotato_Consumption"]:
            axes[0].set_xlabel(variable_name + " (units per month)")
            axes[1].set_ylabel(variable_name + " (units per month)")
        else:
            axes[0].set_xlabel(variable_name)
            axes[1].set_ylabel(variable_name)


        axes[0].set_ylabel("number of people in this " + variable_name + " range")
        axes[0].set_title(variable_name + " histogram")

        # Plot boxplot in the second subplot
        axes[1].boxplot(data[variable_name])
        
        axes[1].yaxis.grid(True, alpha=0.6, linestyle='--')
        axes[1].set_title(variable_name + " boxplot")
        axes[1].set_xlabel("all population")

        # Adjust layout to prevent overlap
        plt.tight_layout()

        # Display the plots
        plt.show()
        print()
    else:
        print(variable_name)
        print(f"mean: {data[variable_name].mean():.3f}")
        print(f"variance: {data[variable_name].var():.3f}")
        print("median: ", data[variable_name].median())
        print("min: ", data[variable_name].min())
        print("max: ", data[variable_name].max())

        # Report on outliers - values that are outside the whiskers of the boxplot
        print()
        print("outliers where 0 is included:")
        q1 = data[variable_name].quantile(0.25)
        q3 = data[variable_name].quantile(0.75)
        iqr = q3 - q1
        lower_bound = q1 - (1.5 * iqr)
        upper_bound = q3 + (1.5 * iqr)
        print("total number of outliers: ", len(data[(data[variable_name] < lower_bound) | (data[variable_name] > upper_bound)]))
        print("number of outliers above: ", len(data[data[variable_name] > upper_bound]))
        print("number of outliers below: ", len(data[data[variable_name] < lower_bound]))

        print()
        print("outliers where 0 is excluded:")
        data_without_0 = data[data[variable_name] != 0]
        q1 = data_without_0[variable_name].quantile(0.25)
        q3 = data_without_0[variable_name].quantile(0.75)
        iqr = q3 - q1
        lower_bound = q1 - (1.5 * iqr)
        upper_bound = q3 + (1.5 * iqr)
        print("total number of outliers: ", len(data_without_0[(data_without_0[variable_name] < lower_bound) | (data_without_0[variable_name] > upper_bound)]))
        print("number of outliers above: ", len(data_without_0[data_without_0[variable_name] > upper_bound]))
        print("number of outliers below: ", len(data_without_0[data_without_0[variable_name] < lower_bound]))
        

        # Create a figure with two subplots side by side
        fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=3, figsize=(12, 6))

        # Plot histogram in the first subplot
        axes[0].hist(data[variable_name], bins=30)
        axes[0].set_xlabel(variable_name + " (units per month)")
        axes[0].set_ylabel("number of people in this " + variable_name + " range")
        axes[0].set_title(variable_name + " histogram")

        # Plot boxplot in the second subplot
        axes[1].boxplot(data[variable_name])
        axes[1].set_ylabel(variable_name + " (units per month)")
        axes[1].yaxis.grid(True, alpha=0.6, linestyle='--')
        axes[1].set_title(variable_name + " boxplot")
        axes[1].set_xlabel("all population (including 0)")

        # Plot boxplot in the third subplot

# for every categorial and binary variable make bar plot and report of number of unique values and most frequent value
for variable_name in categorical_variables_list:
    categories = data[variable_name].unique()
    value_counts_sorted = data[variable_name].value_counts().reindex(categories)

    if variable_name == "Numerical_Age_Category":
        categories = [str(i) for i in sorted(data[variable_name].unique())]
        value_counts_sorted = data[variable_name].value_counts().reindex(sorted(data[variable_name].unique()))
    elif variable_name == "Age_Category":
        categories = [str(i) for i in sorted(data[variable_name].unique(), key=lambda x: int(x[:2]))]
        value_counts_sorted = data[variable_name].value_counts().reindex(categories)
    elif variable_name == "Checkup":
        categories = ['Never', '5 or more years ago', 'Within the past 5 years', 'Within the past 2 years', 'Within the past year']
        value_counts_sorted = data[variable_name].value_counts().reindex(categories)
    elif variable_name == "General_Health":
        categories = ['Poor', 'Fair', 'Good', 'Very Good', 'Excellent']
        value_counts_sorted = data[variable_name].value_counts().reindex(categories)

    print(variable_name)
    print("number of unique values: ", len(data[variable_name].unique()))
    print("most frequent value: ", data[variable_name].value_counts().idxmax())

    # This ensures that value counts are in the same order as 'categories'


    plt.bar(categories, value_counts_sorted)

    if variable_name == "Checkup" or variable_name == "Age_Category":
        plt.xticks(rotation=90) 
    plt.xlabel(variable_name)
    plt.ylabel("number of people with this " + variable_name)
    plt.title(variable_name + " bar plot")
    plt.show()
    print()
